Brief Hospital Course:
___ year old F with history of AIDS (last CD4 count ___, 
ESRD on HD, herpes zoster ophthalmicus c/b post-herpetic 
neuralgia presenting with worsening right facial pain and new 
blisters.

# Face rash and pain- Patient has chronic right face pain 
secondary zoster with opthamalogic involvment of her right eye 
in ___. Patient notes increasing pain over region over the last 
several weeks. She denies any visual changes and says has 
pruitis over the area. On admission, her vitals signs were at 
baseline (SBP 90-100) and she was afebrile with normal WBC. On 
physical exam, she had 5 ulcerations of r cheek with exoriation 
of skin. No vesicles were appreciated. She had pustular lesions 
above her right eye. A DFA was sent and she was empirically 
started on IV acyclovir given history of disseminated zoster and 
recent increase in headaches as well. Optho was consulted in the 
ED and was not concerned for dendritic involvement. Dermatology 
and ID services were consulted on admission. Derm took a L arm 
biopsy and a right face biopsy and recommended continuing IV 
acyclovir as they did could not be 100% sure it was not zoster. 
Her DFA came back as coag negative staph and all acyclovir was 
stopped are consultation of both ID and Derm. Biopsy most 
consistent with an eosinophilic dermatitis. Ms. ___ was 
continued on her hydroxazine and started on Mupirocin Cream 2%. 
ID had recommended starting a course of cephalexin for Impetigo 
but dermatology did not believe that was indicated. Her 
ulcerations, pain, and pustular lesions were greatly improved at 
the time of discharge. She continues to have some pain which she 
says has not been controlled in the past with gabapentin. 
Further treatments for neuropathic pain should be considered as 
an outpatient.

#Headache with photphobia: Patient has a history of chronic 
headaches but says her headahces have increased in frquency and 
pain over the last several weeks and are occasionally associated 
with photophobia. She denies any history of nausea or vomiting 
or neck stiffness. A CT scan head, MRI head w/o contrast, and LP 
were all within normal limits. Her LP was specifically negative 
for elevated WBC, protein, crypto, toxo, and viral cultures were 
negative. Her headaches were moderately contolled with 
oxycodone. She has tried triptan therapy and NSAIDS with no 
success in the past.

# ESRD on dialysis: Patient was followed by renal during 
admission and received HD MWF. Her home dose of selevemer was 
doubled during admission.

# Atrial fibrillation: Patient has a history of paroxysmal Afib 
in past and is not on rate control and takes aspirin daily.  She 
had an episode of afib with rvr to 150 which spontaneously 
resolved after 5 min. She was asymptomatic at the time. 

# AIDS: CD4 count of 14 most recently. She was continued on her 
HAART therapy in addition to bactrim and azithro prophylaxis.

#Shortness of breath: Pt has shortness of breath with exertion 
for several years with several workups without diagnosis. 
Previous echos have showed mild pulmonary hypertension. Her LDH 
was elevated raising concern for PCP however ___ CT scan showed no 
ground glass opacities. On physical exam she had good air entry 
and o2 saturation was at baseline.

Transitions of Care:
1. Pt will follow up with Dr. ___ further management
2.Pt will go home with home ___
3. She will need sutures removed in 1 week from face and 2 weeks 
from arm

radiology.text:
COMPUTED TOMOGRAPHY OF THE THORAX

INDICATION:  HIV, concern for pneumocystis pneumonia, evaluation for
ground-glass opacities.

COMPARISON:  CTA from ___.

TECHNIQUE:  Volumetric CT acquisitions over the entire thorax in inspiration,
no administration of intravenous contrast material, multiplanar
reconstructions.

FINDINGS:  The examination is compared to a CTA chest from ___.

No evidence of incidental thyroid findings.  Unchanged numerical increase of
normal sized or slightly enlarged supraclavicular, infraclavicular, axillary
and mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy.  In unchanged manner, a patent left
superior vena cava is seen and multiple thoracic collateral vessels are
visualized, resulting from stenosis of the left subclavian and brachiocephalic
vein.  Unchanged calcifications of the ascending and descending aorta. 
Unchanged mild valvular and coronary calcifications.  Unchanged CVL in the
inferior vena cava.

No abnormalities along the esophagus.  No osteolytic lesions.  Normal height
of the vertebral bodies.  Normal appearance of the sternum and the ribs.

Several non-characteristic millimetric subpleural granulomas that require no
CT followup.  2 cm rounded ground-glass opacity subpleurally in the right
lower lobe (4A, 123).  Non-characteristic scar in the right lower lobe (4A,
119).  Non-characteristic atelectatic changes in the dependent regions of both
lungs.

Currently, there is no evidence of acute lung disease, in particular no signs
suggestive of PCP.

The pleural surfaces are even.  There are no pleural effusions.

Mild irregularities and thickening of the airway walls suggest mild chronic
airways disease, there is no evidence of endobronchial lesions.

No cystic lung changes.

IMPRESSION:
1.  Unchanged venous collaterals, following known stenosis of the left
subclavian and brachiocephalic vein.

2.  No signs suggestive for PCP.

3.  Several non-characteristic millimetric subpleural granulomas,
uncharacteristic 2 cm ground-glass opacity in the right lower lobe,
potentially infectious in origin, but other causes such as aspiration are also
possible.

4.  No evidence of pleural effusions, signs suggestive of mild chronic airways
disease.  No cystic lung changes.

HISTORY:  Patient with AIDS presenting with worsening headache.  Assess for
intracranial mass.

TECHNIQUE:  Noncontrast axial images obtained through the brain.

COMPARISON:  Comparison is made to head CT performed ___.

FINDINGS:

There is no evidence of acute infarct, hemorrhage, edema large mass or mass
effect.  The ventricles and sulci are slightly prominent consistent with
age-related parenchymal involution.  Stable dense calcifications are noted
along the falx and the cerebellar tentorium, likely related to patient's known
underlying end-stage renal disease.  Stable basal ganglia calcifications. 
Mastoid air cells, middle ear cavities and visualized paranasal sinuses are
clear.  No soft tissue swelling identified.

IMPRESSION:

No evidence of acute intracranial process.

HISTORY:  ___ year-old female with AIDS, CD4 count 10, and VZV neuritis with
worsening headache, concerning for VZV meningitis.  Status post three failed
attempts at lumbar puncture, at the bedside.
 
PROCEDURE:  Fluoroscopic-guided lumbar puncture
 
PHYSICIANS:  Dr. ___ (Neuroradiology attending), Dr. ___
(Neuroradiology fellow).

ANESTHESIA:  Local anesthesia with 1% lidocaine.

PROCEDURE/FINDINGS:  Prior to the procedure, written informed consent was
obtained and the patient showed good understanding of the indications, risks,
benefits and alternatives.

Upon arrival in the angiographic suite, a 'time-out' was performed using
standard ___ protocol.  The patient was placed prone in on the angiographic
table and her lower back was prepped and draped in the typical sterile
fashion.  Local anesthesia was obtained using infiltration with 1% lidocaine. 
Initially, a standard 20 gauge spinal needle was inserted at the level of
L3-4, under fluoroscopic control, but came just short of reaching the spinal
canal, secondary to patient's body habitus.  Subsequently, a longer 20 gauge
spinal needle was inserted into the spinal canal, at the same (L3-4) level,
under fluoroscopic guidance.  Select fluoroscopic pot images were saved to
PACS, for attending review.

A total of 18 mL of clear, colorless cerebrospinal fluid was collected.  The
stylets for both spinal needles were then replaced, and both needles were then
removed, without complication.  Excellent hemostasis was achieved and the
patient was transferred from the angiographic suite in stable condition.

IMPRESSION:  Uncomplicated fluoroscopic-guided lumbar puncture, with 18 mL of
clear cerebrospinal fluid obtained for laboratory analysis and cytology;
results pending.

INDICATION:  ___ woman with AIDS and headache, LP and CT head
nonrevealing, evaluate for lesions.

TECHNIQUE:  Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the brain was obtained without
IV contrast.  Contrast was not administered due to patient's low EGFR.

COMPARISON:  CT head non-contrast of ___.

FINDINGS:  There is mild thickening of the pachymeninges likely
post-procedural. There is no evidence of infarct or hemorrhage.  There is no
evidence of abnormal FLAIR signal throughout the brain parenchyma.  The
ventricles are normal in size.  There is no evidence of mass effect,
hydrocephalus, or midline shift.  The basal cisterns are patent. There is mild
diffuse low signal throughout the bone marrow.

There is mild mucosal thickening of the frontal, ethmoid, sphenoid, maxillary,
and mastoid air cells.  Small mucous retention cysts are visualized in both
maxillary sinuses.

Prominent lymphoid tissue in the nasopharynx.

IMPRESSION:  No infarct or hemorrhage.  No evidence of abnormal FLAIR signal
that could suggest a parenchymal process in this non contrast MRI.
